{{Asia-archaeology-stub}}

'''Christian A. R. Christensen''' (17 December 1906 – 27 January 1967) was a Norwegian newspaper editor. He is known for his work in the [[Norwegian resistance movement]], as editor of ''[[Verdens Gang]]'' and as a historical writer. He also helped shape the [[Ethical Code of Practice for the Norwegian Press]].
==Early life== He was born in [[Solum, Norway|Solum]] as a son of merchant Nils Christian Christensen (1872–1957) and his wife Ellen Kristine Reiersen (1883–1953). He was a brother of [[Nils-Reinhardt Christensen]]. Following miscellaneous education,<ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia|year=|volume=|title=Christian A R Christensen|encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Arne|last=Bonde|authorlink=Arne Bonde|editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]]|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Christian_A_R_Christensen/utdypning|language=Norwegian|accessdate=9 June 2009}}</ref> he was hired in ''[[Dagbladet]]'' in 1926.<ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia|year=2007|title=Christian Arthur Richard Christensen|encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]]|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|editor=Henriksen, Petter|url=http://www.snl.no/Christian_Arthur_Richard_Christensen|language=Norwegian|accessdate=9 June 2009}}</ref> In 1933 he married Else Marie Østvedt (1906–1982).<ref name=nbl/> They lived in [[Vestre Aker]].<ref name=grini>{{cite book|title=Norsk fangeleksikon. Grinifangene|editor=Giertsen, Børre R.|publisher=Cappelen|location=Oslo|date=1946|page=116|language=Norwegian}}</ref> In 1934 Christensen was hired in the publishing house [[Aschehoug]]. He also wrote news analyses for the [[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation]] [[radio]].<ref name=nbl/> Also, Christiansen was a deputy member of the [[Liberal Party of Norway]] national board.<ref name=nkl>{{cite encyclopedia|last=Dahl|first=Hans Fredrik|authorlink=Hans Fredrik Dahl|editor=Dahl, Hans Fredrik|encyclopedia=[[Norsk krigsleksikon 1940-45]]|title=Christensen, Christian A.R.|url=http://mediabase1.uib.no/krigslex/c/c1.html#christensen-christian|accessdate=9 June 2009|year=1995|publisher=Cappelen|volume=|location=Oslo|isbn=|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130929024655/http://mediabase1.uib.no/krigslex/c/c1.html#christensen-christian|archivedate=29 September 2013|df=}}</ref>
==World War II== In 1940, Norway was [[Operation Weserübung|invaded]] and [[German occupation of Norway|occupied by Germany]] as a part of [[World War II]]. Christiansen participated for the Liberal Party in early negotiations with the occupying power, but as Germany seized tighter control in September 1940 Christiansen joined the [[Norwegian resistance movement|Norwegian resistance]],<ref name=nkl/> and acted as a middle man between the Norwegian press and the Home Front. He co-founded the written organ of the Home Front, ''[[Bulletinen]]''. A co-founder was [[Einar Gerhardsen]],<ref name=nbl/> and editors were Christensen, [[Olaf Solumsmoen]] and [[Olav Larssen]].<ref name=nkl/> Christensen also wrote news analyses for several [[Underground media in German-occupied Europe|illegal newspapers]].<ref name=nbl/> He was arrested by the Nazi authorities in late February 1941, for "[[spy]]ing", and sat for three months at [[Møllergata 19]] and for five days in [[Grini concentration camp]].<ref name=grini/> While at Møllergata 19 he penned the crime novel ''Telefon til myrdede'', issued in 1942. He also continued writing news analyses, which were smuggled out of the prison. Upon release in late May 1942, he continued his work.<ref name=nbl/> In 1943 he was arrested for the second time. Via [[Gjerpen]] and [[Larvik]] he was brought to Grini, and sat there from 19 to 31 August.<ref name=grini/>
==Later career== After the war, some members of the Home Front discussed a restart of the newspaper ''[[Tidens Tegn]]'', but this did not go through.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|last=Hjeltnes|first=Guri|authorlink=Guri Hjeltnes|editor=[[Hans Fredrik Dahl|Dahl, Hans Fredrik]]|encyclopedia=Norsk krigsleksikon 1940-45|title=''Tidens Tegn''|url=http://mediabase1.uib.no/krigslex/t/t2.html#tidens-tegn|accessdate=18 June 2009|year=1995|publisher=Cappelen|volume=|location=Oslo|isbn=|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315114629/http://mediabase1.uib.no/krigslex/t/t2.html#tidens-tegn|archivedate=15 March 2012|df=}}</ref> Instead a new newspaper with roots in the Home Front was created, with Christensen as editor-in-chief: ''[[Verdens Gang]]''.<ref name=nbl/> He remained editor-in-chief until his death.<ref name=snl/> From 1953 he co-edited with [[Oskar Hasselknippe]], and he was succeeded by [[Vegard Sletten]].<ref name=snl-vg>{{cite encyclopedia |year=2007 |title=''Verdens Gang''|encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]]|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|editor=Henriksen, Petter|url=http://www.snl.no/Verdens_Gang|language=Norwegian|accessdate=9 June 2009}}</ref> Despite initial hardships,<ref name=nbl/> the newspaper grew influent and has been the largest in Norway since 1981.<ref name=snl-vg/> In 1963 it assumed the [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] format as the first in Norway,<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |year=2007 |title=tabloid|encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]]|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|editor=Henriksen, Petter|url=http://www.snl.no/tabloid|language=Norwegian|accessdate=9 June 2009}}</ref> reportedly to Christensen's dismay.<ref name=henbast>{{cite journal|last=Bastiansen|first=Henrik G.|authorlink=Henrik G. Bastiansen|date=2006|title=Når redaktører dissekeres|journal=[[Prosa]]|volume=12|issue=6|url=http://www.prosa.no/artikkel.asp?ID=101|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101108203146/http://www.prosa.no/artikkel.asp?ID=101|archivedate=2010-11-08|df=}}</ref> Christensen also chaired the [[Norwegian Press Association]] from 1958 to 1962,<ref name=nbl/> and was instrumental in establishing the Rights and Duties of the Editor code in 1953 and for the revision of the [[Ethical Code of Practice for the Norwegian Press]] in 1956.<ref name=henbast/> This was the first revision since the code's inauguration in 1936.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://presse.no/Pressens_Faglige_Utvalg_PFU/Var_Varsom-plakaten/|title=Vær Varsom-plakaten|publisher=[[Norwegian Press Association]]|language=Norwegian|accessdate=9 June 2009|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090625095409/http://presse.no/Pressens_Faglige_Utvalg_pfu/Var_Varsom-plakaten/|archivedate=25 June 2009|df=}}</ref>
He also participated in the non-press sphere after the war; already in 1944 he helped shape the Common Platform (''Fellesprogrammet'') which was meant to unite [[List of political parties in Norway|political parties in Norway]] after the war. In May 1945 he supported [[Paal Berg]], head of [[Hjemmefrontens Ledelse]] in his endeavors to create a broad, non-partisan coalition.<ref name=nkl/> The road was open as the pre-war [[cabinet Nygaardsvold]] resigned, but the increasingly popular [[Communist Party of Norway|Communist Party]] were particularly skeptical to Berg, and the [[Conservative Party of Norway|Conservative]] [[President of the Storting]] [[C. J. Hambro]] got his way in reconvening the pre-war [[Parliament of Norway]]. Berg faced unexpected opposition from this Parliament, and gave up on 20 June. Instead Einar Gerhardsen formed [[Gerhardsen's First Cabinet|a cabinet]], and also won the [[Norwegian parliamentary election, 1945|first free post-war election]].<ref name=furre>{{cite book|title=Norsk historie 1914–2000|first=Berge|last=Furre|authorlink=Berge Furre|year=2000|series=Volume six of ''[[Norsk historie (Samlaget)|Norsk historie]]''|publisher=Det Norske Samlaget|location=Oslo|isbn=|pages=120–122}}</ref>
Christensen was a board member of the [[Norwegian Institute of International Affairs]] and the [[Norwegian News Agency]]. In addition, he continued his writing of historical books. Notable works included ''Fra verdenskrig til verdenskrig'' ('From World War to World War') and ''Okkupasjonsår og etterkrigstid'' ('Occupation Years and Post-war Era'), volumes eight and nine of the series ''Vårt folks historie'' ('Our People's History'), both issued in 1961. He died of a heart attack while on a [[Cruising (maritime)|cruise]] in 1967, in a hospital in [[Las Palmas]].<ref name=nbl/>
