{{Infobox historian
|name=Hasan Beg Rumlu
|birth_date=1530/1531
|birth_place=[[Qom]], [[Safavid dynasty|Safavid Empire]]
|known_for=''Aḥsān al-tawārikh''
|other_names=Hasan Soltan Rumlu{{sfn|Quinn|2003|pages=31-32}}
}}

'''Hasan Beg Rumlu''' ({{Lang-fa|حسن بیگ روملو}}, born 1530 or 1531) was a 16th-century [[Safavid dynasty|Safavid]] military officer and historian. A cavalryman of the ''[[Qurchi (royal bodyguard)|qurchi]]'' corps, he is principally known for his [[chronicle]] of Safavid history; the ''Aḥsān al-tawārikh''.

== Biography ==
Most information about Hasan Beg's life stems from his own work, the ''Aḥsān al-tawārikh'', which he completed in 1578.{{sfn|Quinn|2003|pages=31-32}}{{efn|According to Quinn / ''[[Encyclopædia Iranica]]'' (2003), the ''Aḥsān al-tawārikh'' was "originally intended as a twelve-volume general history, of which only the last two volumes have survived".{{sfn|Quinn|2003|pages=31-32}} According to Quinn & Melville (2012): "he [Hasan Beg Rumlu] was a prolific writer if we are to believe that there were originally twelve volumes in his chronicle".{{sfn|Quinn|Melville|2012|page=213}}}} He was born in [[Qom]], a member of the [[Turkmens|Turkoman]] Rumlu tribe, and the grandson of Amir Soltan Rumlu, a prominent [[Qizilbash]] lord who served during the reign of King (''[[Shah]]'') [[Ismail I]] ({{reign|1501|1524}}).{{sfn|Quinn|2003|pages=31-32}} Hasan Beg's Qizilbash background makes him "somewhat unique in the annals of Safavid historiography".{{sfn|Quinn|Melville|2012|page=213}} After his grandfather's death in 1539 or 1540, Hasan Beg found himself unable to gain command over his grandfather's army, because, according to his own explanation, "he was busy with his unpleasant duties as a ''[[Qurchi (royal bodyguard)|qurchi]]''".{{sfn|Quinn|2003|pages=31-32}} Though a military officer, Hasan Beg "received the sort of training that was typical of a Persian administrator and bureaucrat".{{sfn|Quinn|2003|pages=31-32}} For example, among other subjects he studied works on [[logic]] as well as the art of [[calligraphy]].{{sfn|Quinn|2003|pages=31-32}} 

In 1541–1542, Hasan Beg accompanied King [[Tahmasp I]] ({{reign}}1524–1576) on an expedition to [[Dezful]], and from then he "was with the royal camp in all its journeys, and saw most events with his own eyes, thus becoming an eyewitness to most of the subsequent military events that he described".{{sfn|Quinn|2003|pages=31-32}} In 1546–1547, some five years after the [[Dezful]] campaign, Hasan Beg fought in Tahmasp I's [[Safavid Georgia|Georgian]] campaigns. The last military episode in which Hasan Beg reports his own involvement was Tahmasp I's battle against the [[Ardalan]] Kurds in 1550.{{sfn|Quinn|2003|pages=31-32}} 

Though Hasan Beg does not mention his involvement in succession matters after the death of Tahmasp I, contemporary author Abd-ol-Hossein Nava'i suggests that Hasan Beg sided with the other Rumlu's, who sought to install Prince Ismail Mirza (later known regnally as [[Ismail II]]; {{reign}}1576–1577) on the throne and who were adversaries of the pro-[[Haydar Mirza Safavi|Haydar Mirza]] camp.{{sfn|Quinn|2003|pages=31-32}} Nava'i suggests that Hasan Beg may have been part of the Rumlu ''qurchis'' who took part in the murder of Haydar Mirza. When Ismail II died in 1577, Hasan Beg became part of the royal retinue of his successor, [[Mohammad Khodabanda]] ({{reign}}1578–1587).{{sfn|Quinn|2003|pages=31-32}} 

Hasan Beg's "most enduring legacy is historiographical".{{sfn|Quinn|2003|pages=31-32}} Later Safavid historians (e.g. [[Iskander Beg Munshi]]) used material from Hasan Beg's ''Aḥsān al-tawārikh'' in the sections of their works related to the rule of king Tahmasp I. Hasan Beg's work was used by [[Fazli Isfahani Khuzani]] for his ''Afżal al-tawārikh'' and also survives in "a very late cluster of mostly anonymous semi-fictional accounts of early Safavid history such as the ''ʿĀlamārā-ye Shah Esmāʿil''".{{sfn|Quinn|2003|pages=31-32}} Later historians also quoted material from Hasan Beg's work, even though they did not mention Hasan Beg by name.{{sfn|Quinn|2003|pages=31-32}}

