{{Authority control}} {{DEFAULTSORT:Srpski Rjecnik}} [[Category:Serbian dictionaries]] [[Category:19th century in Serbia]] [[Category:Serbian language]] [[Category:Principality of Serbia]] [[Category:1818 books]] [[Category:History of the Serbs]] [[Category:Cyrillic script]] [[Category:History of the Serbo-Croatian language]]

A scholar at the [[University of Toronto]], '''Theophile James Meek''' (1881–1966) published widely on [[archaeology]], corresponded with [[William Foxwell Albright|Wm. F. Albright]], and was a frequent contributor to the ''[[Encyclopædia Britannica]]'' on subjects related to the archaeology of both [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]] and [[Egypt]].  He may have played a part in working out the chronology of Egypt which soon became the prevailing mainstream chronology among scholars, and which the [[Encyclopedia Americana]] still upholds today.  More recently, the Britannica has lowered its dates somewhat currently, with [[Manfred Bietak]], an eminent [[Egyptologist]] placing them even later.

In the book ''Hebrew Origins'', he suggested that the Conquest of Palestine occurred in two phases: the first being represented by the settlement of the central highlands seen at 1400 BCE, and the second being seen archaeologically in the conquests of the "[[Joshua]]" cities, then dated to around 1250.  He pointed out that the [[Song of Deborah]] ([[Book of Judges|Judges]] ch. 5) does not seem to know the three [[Tribe of Judah|Judah]] territory tribes, but early stages of Joshua do, and that they were thus perhaps transposed in time.

He is also widely cited for having suggested that the "Song of Songs" (a.k.a. the "[[Song of Solomon]]") had striking similarities with a [[Babylon]]ian fertility myth.

